The major drainage of Cumberland Mountain State Park. It flows eastward from the hills to the west for approximately 8.0 km before veering north at its confluence with Coon Hollow Branch. Beyond the dam, Byrd Creek absorbs Threemile Creek, which flows from the west, and continues eastward for another 16 km before empyting into Daddys Creek (a tributary of the Obed River) near Crab Orchard.

A river draining a part of the Cumberland Plateau in Tennessee. The Obed River rises in Cumberland County, Tennessee, just south of Crossville. Shortly after crossing into Morgan County it receives the flow of Daddys Creek. Downstream from this is the mouth of Clear Creek. Several miles below the mouth of Clear Creek is the confluence with the Emory River.

A river in the States of Mississippi and Louisiana. It forms in Winston County, Mississippi from the confluence of Nanawaya and Tallahaga Creeks. It is 790 km long. The Yockanookany and Strong Rivers are tributaries. Northeast of Jackson, the Ross Barnett Reservoir is formed by a dam.

A river, about 130 km long, in southeastern Mississippi in the United States. The river drains an area of about 23,000 km2 and flows into Mississippi Sound of the Gulf of Mexico. The Pascagoula River is formed in northwestern George County by the confluence of the Leaf and Chickasawhay Rivers and flows generally southward through swampy bottomlands in George and Jackson Counties. In its lower course the river forms several channels and bayous; its largest such distributary is the West Pascagoula River, which flows into the Mississippi Sound at Gautier. The main channel passes Escatawpa and Moss Point and flows into the sound at Pascagoula.
A populated place.

A river on the southwest Gulf Coast of Florida in the United States, approximately 121 km long. It drains rural area on the northern edge of the Everglades northwest of Miami. The river issues from Lake Hicpochee, in southeastern Glades County, approximately 16 km WNW of Clewiston. It flows WSW past La Belle, where it becomes tidal, forming an estuary along its lower 40 km. It broadens as it nears the gulf, passing Fort Myers and Cape Coral. It enters the Gulf of Mexico 16 km southwest of Fort Myers in San Carlos Bay protected by Sanibel Island.

The longest river in the State of Florida, stretching 500 km from Indian River County to the Atlantic Ocean in Jacksonville in Duval County. The upper (southern) basin of the river has indistinct banks, with numerous sloughs and lagoons, often pooling into ponds and lakes. Some of the larger lakes are Blue Cypress Lake, Lake Hellen Blazes, Sawgrass Lake, Lake Washington, Lake Winder, Lake Poinsett, Ruth Lake, Puzzle Lake, Lake Harney, Lake Jesup and Lake Monroe. Below Lake Harney, the river is joined by the Econlockhatchee River and runs between higher bluffs on either side, forming the middle basin. This part of the river runs through what is now the Ocala National Forest. The lower (northern) basin begins where the largest tributary of the Saint Johns, the Ocklawaha River, joins the flow. It passes through Palatka, then through unspoiled riverine bottomland hardwoods, pine flatwoods and sandhill communities, on its way to Jacksonville. Past Green Cove Springs, the river becomes an estuary, where fresh and salt water meet, and a wide diversity of living species inhabit the islands, inlets, sounds, streams and marshes of the area.

A very short river in Citrus County, Florida flowing into the Gulf of Mexico. It is just 11 km long, and has a drainage basin of 13 km2, joining Kings Bay to the Gulf of Mexico. The river's significance is in the thirty natural springs that add an average of 1,135 million liters of warm water to the river every day.

A river, approximately 180 km long in the State Florida. The river's large watershed, known as the ACF River Basin for short, drains an area of approximately 50,505 km2 into the Gulf of Mexico. It is formed on the state line between Florida and Georgia, near the town of Chattahoochee, Florida, approximately 60 mi northeast of Panama City, by the confluence of the Flint and Chattahoochee rivers. The actual confluence is submerged in the Lake Seminole reservoir formed by the Jim Woodruff Dam. It flows generally south through the forests of the Florida Panhandle, past Bristol. In northern Gulf County, it receives the Chipola River from the west. It flows into Apalachicola Bay, an inlet of the Gulf of Mexico, at Apalachicola.

A fast running river originating in Georgia, and terminating in Florida. The Ochlockonee originates south of the town of Sylvester in Worth County in southwest Georgia discharging to Ochlockonee Bay, then into Apalachee Bay, in Florida. In Florida, the river forms the western boundaries of Leon County and Wakulla County and eastern boundaries of Gadsden County, Liberty County, and Franklin County. The Ochlockonee flows through the Red Hills, Talquin State Forest, Lake Talquin State Park and the Apalachicola National Forest, and past Ochlockonee River State Park, where it is tidally influenced and a mixture of fresh, brackish, and salt water, on the way to its terminus in Ochlockonee Bay, which then empties into Apalachee Bay.
